Switzerland, also hopes this month to conclude negotiations on free trade
pacts with Hungary and Poland. Mr Renk said talks with Hungary had made good
progress, despite earlier complaints by Budapest that Efta countries were
insisting on tougher terms than the EC, with whom Hungary, Poland and
Czechoslovakia all have association accords.
Outstanding problems concern trade in farm goods, where Efta countries have
shown themselves reluctant to open their markets to cheaper east European
produce.
